Resource Investing News Featured Stock




Advantage Lithium – Building an International Lithium Empire: Nevada, Mexico and Argentina



Overview
Advantage Lithium Corp. (TSXV:AAL; OTCQX:AVLIF) is a Vancouver based resource company focused on the strategic acquisition, exploration and development of lithium properties. With a goal of growing through acquisition as well as through the drill bit, the company is quickly building a global lithium empire with strategic exploration projects within the epicenters of three of the world’s lithium hotspots: Nevada, Mexico and Argentina.
In Nevada, Advantage Lithium has partnered with Nevada Sunrise (TSXV:NEV) on a portfolio of five lithium brine projects in the Clayton Valley and Lida Valley regions. Clayton Valley is home to North America’s only lithium brine operation, Albemarle’s Silver Peak mine. Four of these projects are drill-ready, having completed Nevada’s complex permitting process. Advantage Lithium’s access to water rights make the company a standout from its peers within Nevada’s lithium triangle where water rights have been over-appropriated.
In Mexico, the company has partnered with Radius Gold Inc. (TSXV:RDU) in a portfolio of four lithium brine exploration projects located in Mexico. These properties are located in large, closed basins in geological settings analogous with the Clayton Valley basin.
Advantage Lithium’s latest portfolio edition is the Stella Marys project in the province of Salta, within Argentina’s Lithium Triangle. Salta is ranked by Fraser Institute as one of the most favorable jurisdictions in Central and South America for exploration. The region is home to two producing lithium mines—Orocobre’s Olaroz and FMC’s Salar de Hombre Muerto.
Advantage Lithium says it’s ready to do the real work of exploring and developing at its JV lithium properties, and management has a long-term goal of taking the company to producer status. A six-hole program is planned for Q3 2016 at the company’s flagship Clayton NE project.
“With a drill program soon to start at our Clayton NE project in Nevada, a recent agreement to acquire four exciting early-stage projects in Mexico and now, this more advanced project next to Orocobre’s large and shallow resource at Salar de Salinas Grandes, we are closer to fulfilling our goal as a leading junior in the lithium space,” commented David Sidoo, President and CEO of Advantage Lithium.
The company is led by a group of award-winning company builders with a track record of success in creating maximum shareholder value, including Fission Uranium Founder and CEO Dev Randhawa; American Oil & Gas Founder and significant shareholder David Sidoo; and Fission Uranium President, COO and Chief Geologist Ross McElroy.
In August 2016, Advantage Lithium announced the closing of a financing with gross proceeds of $4.025 million and another round of financing was announced in early September for up to an additional $5.04 million.
Investment Highlights 

5 lithium brine projects (4 drill-ready) in the Clayton Valley and Lida Valley region.
Proximal to North America’s only producing lithium brine operation—Albermarle’s Silver Peak mine; Clayton NE border only 110 meters from several Silver Peak production wells.
Drilling at Clayton NE to begin in Q3 2016.
Brine deposits typically have lower exploration and operating costs than hard rock deposits.
Advantage Lithium JV is the only lithium exploration company with access to water rights in the Clayton Valley basin where the state of Nevada has over-appropriated water rights.
Four lithium brine exploration projects in mining-friendly Mexico in large, salar closed basins in geological settings analogous to the Clayton Valley basin.
Stella Marys project immediately adjacent to Orocobre’s large, shallow depth, inferred resource in Argentina’s Lithium Triangle.
Award-winning management team of successful company builders.
Advantage Lithium is now a Tier One company. 

Key Properties: Clayton Valley and Lida Valley, Nevada
 Under its earn-in agreement with Nevada Sunrise, Advantage Lithium has the option to acquire a 70 percent stake in three of the projects and a 50 percent stake in the remaining two projects.

Advantage Lithium also has the right to earn 100 percent of the Nevada Water Right Permit 44411, held by Nevada Sunrise. Water rights are a prerequisite to success for any company in Nevada planning to bring a lithium brine project through development and into production.
Flagship Project: Clayton NE
The Clayton NE property covers 1,000 acres of land in Nevada’s Clayton Valley and is contiguous to the eastern boundary of Albemarle’s Silver Peak mine. Several of the lithium brine production wells at Silver Peak are situated within 110 meters west of the Clayton NE project’s claim boundary.
Historical data on the property includes drill-hole CV-5 which was part of a regional drill program conducted by the United States Geological Survey (USGS) in 1977. The hole was drilled to a depth of 479 feet and encountered lithium values in ground water ranging from 24 ppm to 110 ppm, averaging 69.3 ppm for a group of 11 samples, and averaging 65.75 ppm for another group of 12 samples.

Advantage Lithium believes additional aquifers potentially hosting brines of similar or better contents of lithium could be intersected by deeper drilling. In Q3 2016, the company plans to commence a 6-hole drill program at Clayton NE targeting the Silver Peak border.
Jackson Wash
 The Jackson Wash lithium project covers 3,320 acres in Nevada’s Lida Valley Basin located 30 kilometers southeast of the Silver Peak mine of Clayton Valley. The under-explored Lida Valley is analogous in sedimentary formations and underlying structures to Clayton Valley.
In 2011, historical exploration conducted on the property included sampling and geological surveying. Sampling at six locations returned lithium values ranging from 97.3 ppm lithium to 117.0 ppm lithium. A detailed gravity survey and two CSAMT lines surveyed by a previous operator were interpreted as a layered sequence of unconsolidated, saturated alluvial sediments filling a deep basin beneath the valley floor.

Advantage Lithium believes the property has the potential to host a reservoir of lithium brine within an outlined gravity low. The company has planned a three to four-hole drill program to test specific structural and stratigraphic targets believed prospective for lithium brine deposits. In February 2016, the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) granted a drill permit for up to 10 holes over two years.
Gemini
 The Gemini lithium project covers 4,950 acres in the Lida Valley Basin and is located 40 kilometers southeast of the Clayton Valley basin. Between 2012 to 2013, a University of Texas geological research team conducted gravity surveys in the Lida Valley. The resulted indicate strong gravity lows within two faulted sub-basins (Gemini West and Gemini East) approximately 7 kilometers apart and hundreds of meters deep.
In early 2016, results from two moving-loop TDEM surveys carried out on the Gemini property by Nevada Sunrise detected a conductive layer 150 meters to 250 meters deep which appears to cover most of Gemini West and Gemini East sub-basins. Several isolated strong conductive zones were interpreted at depths from 400 meters to 600 meters indicating the potential for lithium-rich brine within the sub-basins.

The BLM has granted permits for 10 exploration drill holes at Gemini to test the sub-basins for lithium-bearing brines.
Neptune
 The Neptune lithium project covers 6,320 acres in the southwest Clayton Valley basin and is located about 15 kilometers to the north of Silver Peaks in an active area for lithium mining and exploration. Historical geophysical data indicates the property has the potential to host lithium brines in subterranean aquifers.
The BLM has permitted 10 drill holes at Neptune. Nevada Sunrise has completed two drill holes on the property to date. In the first hole, sampling from the intersected strata contained lithium-bearing sediments that averaged 156 ppm lithium over 65.5 meters from 392.7 meters to the end of hole at 457.2 meters, reaching a peak value of 217 ppm lithium. In addition, biogeochemical data collected near the drill holes confirmed anomalous lithium concentrations ranging from 11 ppm up to 35 ppm.

Advantage Lithium is planning a third drill hole up to 2,000 meters deep and approximately 1.6 kilometers east of the first hole. A 2016 geophysical survey interpreted this area to be a potential trap where denser, lithium-bearing brines could migrate and pool.
Aquarius
The Aquarius lithium project covers 1,660 acres in the central Clayton Valley basin, approximately 5 kilometers southwest of the Silver Peak mine.
In March 2016, Nevada Sunrise conducted a TDEM geophysical survey which detected conductive horizons at depths ranging between 250 meters to 450 meters. Advantage Lithium is preparing to submit a permit application to the BLM for a drill program to test for lithium brines at Aquarius.

Key Properties: Chihuahua and Coahuila, Mexico 
 In early September 2016, Advantage Lithium acquired an option to earn up to a 70 percent interest in four lithium brine exploration projects covering a total of 37,000 hectares in the state of Chihuahua and Coahuila, Mexico.



